{
  "doc_id": "15080",
  "text": "Human induced pluripotent (iPS) cells are embryonic stem-(ES-) like pluripotent cells derived from somatic cells by ectopic expression of a defined set of reprogramming factors [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Patient-derived iPS cells are expected to be useful for disease modeling, but the effects of reprogramming by Yamanaka factors on X-inactivation in female iPS cells remain controversial. A previous study showed that human iPS cells exhibit a nonrandom X chromosome inactivation (XCI) pattern because they reflect the XCI status of the single fibroblast from which they were derived [CITATION_3] . Other groups reported two active X chromosomes in iPS cells derived from a patient with Rett syndrome [CITATION_4] . For disease modeling of a manifesting carrier of DMD in vitro, the correct understanding of the XCI status of female iPS cells and hiPS-derived skeletal muscle is needed.",
